# Completion Notification — Read Memory First

**MANDATORY: Before running the final completion speak command (the "Done. [summary]" line), you MUST read the relevant memory or context file that relates to the task just completed.**

## What to read before speaking

| Task type | Read this first |
|-----------|----------------|
| Changes to `friday-listen.py`, `friday-ambient.py`, `friday-speak.py` | Re-read the changed file to confirm what actually changed |
| Changes to `.env` | Re-read `.env` to verify the new values are what you intended |
| Changes to `skill-gateway/src/` (server, memory, alexa) | Re-read the changed file |
| Any other code change | Re-read the primary file you edited |

## Why

The spoken summary **must match reality**. If you speak "Done. Updated silence to five seconds." without re-reading `.env`, you may have mis-stated the actual written value.

## Format

```bash
# 1. Read the relevant file (Read tool) — ALWAYS do this first
# 2. Then speak the summary — ALWAYS block_until_ms: 0 (fire-and-forget, never block)
$OPENCLAW_HOME/scripts/oc-speak.sh "Done. [confirmed summary]."
```

**ALWAYS** use `block_until_ms: 0` on the Shell call — completion summaries are never an exception.

**The spoken summary must be derived from what you read, not from memory of what you intended to write.**
